passages.text: We have been pretty consistent with our thesis, based on three premises: (i) Rational backdrop, (ii) substantial capital returns, and (iii) an appealing setup on the stock (earnings & valuation upside risk). We view these arguments as ongoing and reflect the solid momentum in our near- to medium- term expectations. We upgrade 1H estimates by \(17\%\) , FY26 by \(7\%\) and FY27 onwards by avg. \(4\%\) , sitting comfortably above guidance. We now sit \(10\%\) above the midpoint of company guidance for group Adj. operating profit (JPMc £3.2bn vs range £2.7- 3bn). In our view, the company is unlikely to raise guidance with the 1H26 print in order to retain flexibility to address potential heightened competition (though all signs so far confirm an unchanged status quo within Asda and discounters). However, we do believe the company may narrow the guidance range with this update towards the upper- end, triggering consensus upgrades. With this, we reiterate our OW rating with a revised PT of 450p (end February- 2027) and place the stock on Positive Catalyst Watch into 1H26 earnings on October 2, 2025.

**Upping estimates on higher margin visibility.** With this note, we (i) revise higher our estimates for UK LFL based on sector trends and Worldpanel data, (ii) address EBIT margin assumptions that were relatively conservative prior, including for Tesco Bank, (iii) update FX, risk-free rate, food CPI actuals, and (iv) make modest working capital changes. With this, our PT arrives at 450p (end Feb- 27 vs end Aug- 26 prior). On 2Q, LFLs raised by 1ppt to 5% and 50bps higher margin assumptions to flat y/y, we now model 1H UK retail operating profit at £1550mn, +3% y/y, noting that on such performance our 2H implied expectations still seem conservative enough (LFLs 4%/ margins -50bps y/y, EBIT -7% y/y). Along with £60mn contribution from the Bank, this leads to 1H group EBIT estimates 14% higher than before. Altogether we up 1H estimates by 17%, FY26 by 7% and FY27 onwards by avg. 4%, sitting comfortably above consensus and guidance.

JPMe vs company- compiled consensus: we sit \(10 - 15\%\) above the Street on adj. EPS across FY26 and FY27. On FY26, we are slightly above consensus on UK and ROI LFLs, and \(c4\%\) above on adj. EBIT. We sit c30bps above the Street on group adjusted EBIT margins at \(4.4\%\) , and arrive at a \(c10\%\) higher adj diluted EPS at 30.04p/share. We are further positive into FY27, as we forecast margins recovering from the incremental opex pressures faced in FY26, and anticipate sound momentum with adjusted group EBIT margins at \(4.6\% (+30\) bps vs the Street). With group adjusted operating profit \(+5\%\) vs the Street, we arrive at a \(c14\%\) higher adj diluted EPS at 34.65p/share. Note that Bloomberg and company- compiled consensus estimates do not differ materially on key metrics.

Operating leverage still understated. Consensus estimates imply a c2.5- 3.5% revenue growth run- rate from FY25 to FY27, with group adjusted operating profit in FY26 relatively flat vs FY25 (on an underlying basis). Note that the group adjusted operating profit, ex banking operations, was 2,973m in FY25. Into FY27, the Street estimates modest margin recovery at 4.3% (+20bps y/y). JPM estimates reflect a sharper pick up in FY27, with a c20bps y/y margin bounce to 4.6% and a c7.5% y/y increase on absolute group adjusted operating profit.

Our take: In the four weeks to 10th August 2025, the total market grew \(4.0\%\) vs \(5.4\%\) in the previous four weeks (in the context of 110 bps tougher comps) with grocery price inflation at \(5.0\%\) (slightly down vs \(5.2\%\) prior). Market polarisation continued, with Tesco and Sainsbury still comfortably outperforming Asda and Morrison. The data: Total till roll growth: Market \(+4\%\) , Tesco \(+7.1\%\) , Sainsbury \(+4.8\%\) , Asda \(- 2.1\%\) , Aldi \(+3.2\%\) , Lidl \(+10.3\%\) , Morrisons \(+0.3\%\) . Total till roll market share: Tesco \(+81\) bps, Sainsbury \(+12\) bps, Asda \(- 75\) bps, Aldi \(- 8\) bps, Lidl \(+46\) bps, Morrisons \(- 31\) bps. Continued momentum: The marginal data implies an acceleration vs July for both Tesco and Sainsbury in terms of market share gains with modestly lower growth rates (previous Tesco growth run rate \(+8.2\%\) with market share \(+75\) bps), and Sainsbury (previous Sainsbury growth run rate \(+6.0\%\) with market share \(+10\) bps). Read to our stance: We have an OW stance on both shares based on sound fundamentals and continued execution of the right strategy. Momentum above expectations underpins the shares' re- rating.

No signs of Asda inflection just yet. See our credit analyst Neill Keaney's note (here). The 2Q Asda print reaffirms our view that Asda lacks the capability and firepower to undertake a prolonged and irrational 'price war' in the UK. With guidance revised lower for EBITDA and FCF generation in FY25, and expectations for leverage to continue to (temporarily) worsen, our view is that Asda's fundamentals remain relatively much weaker compared to the sound financial position of TSCO and SBRY. Coupled with Worldpanel data that shows TSCO and SBRY outperformance, vs continued Asda underperformance (MSD% below market, c75bps share loss in latest reported period) and Which? pricing data proving Asda's problems go well beyond price, we reiterate our OW stance on TSCO and SBRY.

Our Take: Tesco delivered sound current trading with a beat on all fronts - UK LFLs at \(5.1\%\) vs consensus at \(4.0\%\) (+110bps). Further, Booker did better-than- expected at \(2.0\%\) (strength in core catering and retail offset tobacco market decline) while Central Europe continued to pick up at \(4.1\%\) LFL (strong performance in food).

**Tesco** (Overweight; Price Target: 450p)

The UK grocery market is rational, and we do not think a price war has yet commenced.Overall, we expect the rational behavior to continue given: 1) the improved execution and relative price positioning at both TSCO and SBRY, in sharp contrast to strategies of margin preservation/maximization at key rivals Asda/Morrison and Discounters (c40% combined market share); 2) food inflation is accelerating; and 3) the UK consumer remains relatively resilient. This combination underpins a rather visible gross margin outlook and therefore our c10% higher-than-consensus expectations.
We value Tesco using a five-year DCF model with a WACC of 10.2% and terminal growth rate of 1%, which yields a fair value of 450p/share (end-February 2027).
